### 5. Why this is "Production Ready"

1.  **Cascading Deletes:** In the Prisma schema, if you delete a `Workout`, all its `WorkoutLogs` and `Sets` are automatically deleted. This prevents orphaned data.
2.  **Global vs Custom Exercises:** The `userId` field in the `Exercise` model is optional. This allows you to ship the app with a library of standard exercises (where `userId` is null) while letting users create their own.
3.  **Indexing & Performance:** PostgreSQL handles the `WorkoutLog` relationships efficiently. For a production app with millions of logs, you would add an index on `Workout(userId)` and `Workout(date)`.
4.  **Security:**
    *   Passwords are never stored in plain text (use `bcrypt`).
    *   Routes are protected by an `authenticateToken` middleware.
    *   Users can only access their own progress and workouts.
5.  **Analytics Ready:** The structure of the `Set` table allows you to easily calculate **Volume** ($sets \times reps \times weight$) or **1RM** (One Rep Max) estimations using the Brzycki formula directly in SQL or TypeScript.

### Example Progress Query (1RM Estimation)
If you wanted to track progress by Estimated 1RM:
```typescript
const logs = await prisma.set.findMany({
  where: { workoutLog: { exerciseId, workout: { userId } } }
});

const progress = logs.map(set => ({
  date: set.workoutLog.workout.date,
  estimated1RM: set.weight * (1 + (set.reps / 30)) // Brzycki formula
}));
```

To build a production-ready multi-language content platform, we need to solve three core challenges: **Data Modeling** (how to associate translations), **Query Performance** (efficiently fetching the right version), and **SEO/UX** (handling URLs and fallbacks).

This solution uses **Next.js 14 (App Router)**, **TypeScript**, **Prisma**, and **PostgreSQL**.

### 1. The Architecture: "The Translation-Table Pattern"

We separate "Content" (the container/metadata) from "Translations" (the actual localized data). This allows a single article to have infinite regional variations (e.g., `en-US`, `en-GB`, `fr-CA`).

---

### 2. Database Schema (Prisma)

```prisma
// schema.prisma

datasource db {
  provider = "postgresql"
  url      = env("DATABASE_URL")
}

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client-js"
}

model Content {
  id        String    @id @default(cuid())
  createdAt DateTime  @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime  @updatedAt
  authorId  String
  status    String    @default("DRAFT") // DRAFT, PUBLISHED

  // Relations
  translations Translation[]

  @@index([status])
}

model Translation {
  id        String   @id @default(cuid())
  contentId String
  locale    String   // e.g., "en-US", "fr-FR", "pt-BR"
  title     String
  body      String   @db.Text
  slug      String   // Unique per locale
  excerpt   String?

  content   Content  @relation(fields: [contentId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)

  @@unique([contentId, locale]) // Only one translation per language per content
  @@unique([slug, locale])      // Slugs must be unique within a language
  @@index([locale])
}
```

---

### 3. The Content Service (Backend Logic)

This service handles the logic for fetching content with a "fallback" mechanism. If a regional variation (e.g., `en-GB`) doesn't exist, it can fall back to a base language (`en`).

```typescript
// lib/services/content-service.ts
import { prisma } from "@/lib/prisma";

export type Locale = string;

export async function getContentBySlug(slug: string, locale: Locale) {
  // 1. Try to find the exact slug and locale
  let translation = await prisma.translation.findFirst({
    where: { slug, locale },
    include: { content: true }
  });

  // 2. Fallback logic: If not found, try to find the content in the base language
  // In a real app, you'd store the 'baseLocale' on the Content record.
  if (!translation && locale.includes('-')) {
    const baseLang = locale.split('-')[0];
    translation = await prisma.translation.findFirst({
      where: { 
        content: { translations: { some: { slug } } },
        locale: { startsWith: baseLang }
      },
      include: { content: true }
    });
  }

  return translation;
}

export async function createLocalizedContent(data: {
  authorId: string;
  translations: {
    locale: string;
    title: string;
    body: string;
    slug: string;
  }[];
}) {
  return await prisma.content.create({
    data: {
      authorId: data.authorId,
      translations: {
        createMany: {
          data: data.translations
        }
      }
    }
  });
}
```

---

### 4. Dynamic Routing & SEO (Frontend)

In Next.js, we use a `[locale]` segment to handle routing. We also implement `generateMetadata` for SEO (crucial for multi-language sites).

```tsx
// app/[locale]/posts/[slug]/page.tsx
import { getContentBySlug } from "@/lib/services/content-service";
import { notFound } from "next/navigation";
import { Metadata } from "next";

interface Props {
  params: { locale: string; slug: string };
}

// SEO: Generate hreflang tags to tell Google about alternate versions
export async function generateMetadata({ params }: Props): Promise<Metadata> {
  const post = await getContentBySlug(params.slug, params.locale);
  if (!post) return {};

  return {
    title: post.title,
    description: post.excerpt,
    alternates: {
      canonical: `https://example.com/${params.locale}/posts/${params.slug}`,
      languages: {
        'en-US': `https://example.com/en-US/posts/${post.slug}`,
        'fr-FR': `https://example.com/fr-FR/posts/${post.slug}`,
      },
    },
  };
}

export default async function PostPage({ params }: Props) {
  const post = await getContentBySlug(params.slug, params.locale);

  if (!post) {
    notFound();
  }

  return (
    <article className="max-w-2xl mx-auto py-10">
      <header className="mb-8">
        <span className="text-sm text-blue-600 uppercase font-bold">
          {params.locale}
        </span>
        <h1 className="text-4xl font-extrabold mt-2">{post.title}</h1>
      </header>

      <div 
        className="prose prose-lg"
        dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: post.body }} 
      />
    </article>
  );
}
```

