### 3. Key Technical Decisions Explained

#### 1. Security via PostgreSQL RLS
Instead of relying on `WHERE doctor_id = '...'` in every single API call (where a developer could easily forget one), RLS acts as a global filter. If a malicious doctor tries to call `GET /api/patients/123` where `123` belongs to someone else, Postgres will return "Not Found" because the RLS policy evaluates to false.

#### 2. Supabase Auth
The `auth.uid()` function in Postgres is cryptographically signed. When a doctor logs in, Supabase issues a JWT. Every request to the database includes this JWT. Postgres decodes it, finds the User ID, and applies it to the `USING` clause of our RLS policies.

#### 3. Database Triggers (Best Practice)
To ensure every new user has a `profile` row, add this trigger:

```sql
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION public.handle_new_user()
RETURNS trigger AS $$
BEGIN
  INSERT INTO public.profiles (id, full_name)
  VALUES (new.id, new.raw_user_meta_data->>'full_name');
  RETURN new;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql SECURITY DEFINER;

CREATE TRIGGER on_auth_user_created
  AFTER INSERT ON auth.users
  FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE PROCEDURE public.handle_new_user();
```

