        {/* Main Feed */}
        <div className={`lg:col-span-3 ${gridStyles[group.group_type as keyof typeof gridStyles]}`}>
          {posts.map(post => (
            <PostRenderer key={post.id} type={group.group_type as any} post={post as any} />
          ))}
        </div>

        {/* Sidebar for Rules */}
        <div className="lg:col-span-1 space-y-6">
          <div className="bg-white p-6 rounded-xl border shadow-sm">
            <div className="flex items-center gap-2 mb-4 font-semibold text-gray-900">
              <ShieldCheck className="w-5 h-5 text-green-600" />
              <h2>Group Rules</h2>
            </div>
            <ul className="space-y-3">
              {group.rules.map((rule, i) => (
                <li key={i} className="text-sm text-gray-600 flex gap-2">
                  <span className="font-bold text-gray-400">{i + 1}.</span> {rule}
                </li>
              ))}
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </main>
  );
}
```

### Key Technical Decisions

1.  **JSONB Content**: Using a single `content` field for posts instead of specific columns (like `image_url` or `code_snippet`) allows the app to grow. If you add a "Music" group tomorrow, you just add a new `MusicPost.tsx` and the database already supports the new data structure.
2.  **Strategy Pattern**: The `PostRenderer` acts as a strategy selector. This keeps the main page logic clean. You can change how a "Photography" group looks globally by editing just one file.
3.  **Layout Separation**: I used a conditional `gridStyles` object in the main page. This ensures that while Photography posts are in a tight grid (like Instagram), Writing posts are stacked vertically with wide margins (like Medium).
4.  **Modular Rule System**: Storing rules as an array in the DB allows the `GroupHeader` to render them dynamically, ensuring every group feels unique not just in visuals, but in governance.

